,Recommended,214340,19121373,"Posted: 16 November, 2015",all,Orangestar,"This is going to be kind of a rambly review because... I... I... don't know. I don't know what to say about Deponia.It's got some hilarious writing, especially for an adventure game, and I got through most of it without a walkthrough, so those are some good points.The art in the game is spectacular. Like, really spectacular... until you get to the cutscenes, where they look like strewn-together flash animations. It still looks good enough that I can let it pass.But... there's something about when the game says it's going to sit down, shut up, and be serious when it feels like something's amiss. The game just... can't be serious. Too much silly stuff is going on.I really like the way the game presents itself, as sort of a set of 3 open-world-y ""scenes"" where you have to work out the puzzles throughout each scene, and get to see the place turn to chaos as you slowly manipulate everything for your personal gain. It also fits the protagonist very well. Hell, the protagonist is basically the epitome of adventure game protagonists. He's basically how an AGP would actually act. He's actually kind of annoying to play as sometimes for that reason, but it kind of delivers with him a message about the genre. It's silly, and really shows Daedalic's writing style.I just feel like there's so much about the world we haven't been informed about though. I guess that's why Deponia is a trilogy, but it feels a tinge too short to make it worth being released in a trilogy.The game is weird and silly and a whole lot of fun and hilarity, but it's just the ending that makes it fall flat, when you realize you've hit the ending and there's quite a few loose ends to tie up in the later sequels,Iadorethe setting in the game. It's beautiful, and I so badly want to explore it more. All the little eccentricities of the world really show itself off. Daedalic seems to be absolutely god-tier at worldbuilding, and if you really like a world that feels like it's full of life, you should check out this game. Heck, the stellar worldbuilding gets you so attached to the world that it makes a later twist in the game all that much more impactful. Too bad our protagonist doesn't share the same views.I'll probably amend this if I ever get the other games in the series, but right now Deponia is standing as ""a pretty good adventure game"". I do recommend it, but be warned that what you're getting into is a little below par."
