,Recommended,214340,16256954,"Posted: 8 June, 2015",all,talgaby,"Short version: 83%The first part of the Deponia trilogy isn’t exactly a bold game that tries to discover new territories in mechanics or storytelling; it’s just a well-constructed point ‘n’ click with proven character concepts, plot mechanics, and puzzles.Long version:The Deponia series is arguably Daedelic Entertainment’s most famous point and click title. Yet the first instalment, for the most part, is just another good adventure game, nothing more.The protagonist, Rufus, is a stereotypical egocentric jerk who just wants to achieve his one goal in life (leave his home for good), no matter how much grief it causes to everyone around him. When the other main character, Goal from the (literally) upper society drops into his life, he sees her only as a ticket out… but eventually gets entangled in a much larger plot, which– the game being the first part of a trilogy– naturally ends in a cliffhanger.What makes this often seen story stereotype work is the writing. The dialogues are perfect from Rufus’ self-centric monologues to the sarcastic responses he gets from everyone else; the characters may be simple, but they have a good synergy.The puzzles are what one expects from a point ‘n’ click: mostly inventory and map hotspot manipulation, with a few occasional (and skippable) minigames. The difficulty is moderate; if you know how adventure game logic works, you shouldn’t have problems– except for maybe the middle segment, which require some trial and error.As a final word: the trilogy was re-released as a single game, making these individual titles somewhat obsolete… unless you want to play the famous drugglejug mode, which was never implemented in the Complete Edition."
