76561198033802030,Recommended,214340,4203760,"Posted: 4 April, 2013",all,sudo sandwich,"Yay, after many years, I get to play another humor adventure game. So how does Deponia measure up?To begin with I very much like the art style. It's got 2D fully animated characters with some pretty nice painted backgrounds. Everything's easy to move around and interact with. Thankfully you can double click to instant-move to a location.Music is serviceable. I like to think of it as elevator music. It's there, and you notice it, but it won't stick, may irritate after a while, and you'd probably rather listen to your own music.The story is all right. The main character is perhaps a little too genuinely self-centered, but he gets better... somewhat... I think...The game's humor falls a bit on the flat side, which is a shame. I don't think I had a laugh out loud moment, just some grins here and there. I was willing to ignore it though, in order to find out what happens next. I admit I'm more than curious as to what is going on with Elysian physiology, but that wasn't answered in the first game, so I guess I'll have to play through the next (two?).Now for the meat and potatoes of the game - the puzzles. This is where I feel the game was lacking. There are several areas where you are just bombarded with random items you pick up, and very poor clues as to where to go or what to do. Ordinarily I do my best to avoid guides, but I ended up using one for this game. It didn't even feel rewarding for the stuff I DID manage to figure out on my own.I guess I'd rate this game a 7/10. It's no King's Quest, it's certainly no Monkey Island."
