,Recommended,214340,9969353,"Posted: 29 April, 2014",all,Offline,"Deponia is a good little point and click adventure game. It has its share of tedious puzzles but most of them are good and makes sense (not a la Discworld). The story is good enough although very linear (we can argue a story is always linear :p ) in my opinion. We are far from games or stories such as the Longest Journey or Monkey Island.The recommended inventory system using the mouse wheel is extremely good and works very well, you can also hit the space bar at anytime to highlight every clickable objects in an area and the hand drawn graphics are really fantastic.I noticed a few bugs here and there, some of the clickable objects would eventually become non-clickable, and sometimes, the dialogue options are sometime off screen (probably not optimized for my resolution ?). The dialogues are well written and the actors did a great work in my opinion but the sound is not normalized very well making it sometime an inaudible mess.Finally, I want to mention that Rufus (the hero) goofiness only worked halfway for me. He is very one dimensional and his lines became very repetitive quickly. Some other characters such as Toni, Kuvac's mayor or Lotti are just more interesting making the world of Deponia a very believable one.If you can go through all the above, then yes, I think you will like Deponia."
76561198095941559,Recommended,214340,9344618,"Posted: 4 March, 2014",all,candiceb,"A fun point & click adventure... not quite up to the Lucas Arts glory days, but still fun.You play as Rufus - oxygen thief pretty much sums him up, but so much so that he ends up being likeable.  The other characters are amusing and the world is interesting - a trash heap planent, a city in the sky & hints of class warfare:  I want to know more, so guess I'm going to have to play the other 2 games in the trilogy.For the most part, the puzzles make sense.  Where they don't & other characters don't give you helpful hints, you generally have few enough inventory items & interaction options to go through the trial & error grind without having too many murderous thoughts.  A nice touch to bypass any frustrating pixel hunting - pressing the spacebar shows you all the objects you can interact with.Overall, a nice diversion.  Not going to blow you away, but still worthwhile."
