76561198052784712,Not Recommended,214340,10176032,"Posted: 19 May, 2014",all,chaostheory66821,"The artistic style is visualy appealing, and the game itself is stable, but there are a lot of tedious elements to this game that don't quite add up. The puzzles aren't exactly connect the dots, more a combination of complete trial and error and hunt and peck. The story, although there, is brought to an almost complete hult by the puzzle mechanics in the game. Usually, a game like this tries to give you enough input that you still have challenging puzzles to figure out, but keeps things flowing enough that the story progresses in a fluent manner; not so much with Deponia.The game is bogged down by constant running around, back and forth, through the same areas, over and over again--which can get old rather quickly--and re-talking to the same people, time and time again, in order to get new items and information after every completed step, that it starts to bog down. Often times, the way that puzzles are put together (if you can even call most of them puzzles) gets old. Including how you are supposed to combine inventory items, and the silly things you are supposed to do in the environment to trigger actions.These elements get in the way of what could be a really great game. I enjoyed parts of Deponia, and detested others. A hate to give this game a 'no' recommendation, because of the clear presentation and easy interface, but unless you are a hardcore fan of point and click gaming that is more hunt and peck than puzzle based, and you have lots of time on your hands, this probably isn't the title for you. Certain puzzles make no logical sense and even seem hindering, especially when other solutions seem more readily available, but are completely unavailable. Puzzle and story should be singlular and lead into one another and Deponia is lacking in this respect. If the developer can improve on these elements in future releases then they will have an outstanding product!"
