,Recommended,214340,8208532,"Posted: 22 December, 2013",all,sandman,"A seriously entertaining point-and-click adventure game that is quite reminiscent of the Monkey Island series. Deponia features brilliant art direction, solid voice acting, and awesome soundtrack (Huzzah!). On the downside, like stated by many, the game isridiculouslyshort – I think it took like 5 hours in my first playthrough (apparently, this is the first installation of a trilogy, so fingers crossed for the next games). Even though the puzzles (which you can skip) are mostly fun, sometimes it gets quite tricky to find the right combination of items when you have to improvise – there were couple of instances where I gave up logic and instead tried every possible combination with the interactive objects. And when I finally figured them out, I was like “Seriously?Really?” But such instances were admittedly rare and definitely not the norm. On a somewhat surprising note, when I checked the texture compression option (which enables real-time compression), I started noticing a slight mouse lag and longer black screens during area transitions. Although it says that enabling that feature demands “high processing power”,  it’s funny to have a point-and-click gamelagon a machine that runs the likes of the Witcher 2 or Crysis 3 with high/ultra settings (then again, it could be Windows 8.1 acting up as usual). Overall, highly recommended."
,Recommended,214340,4260971,"Posted: 9 August, 2012",all,Xelios,"A humorous 2D point & click adventure in which you play as Rufus, an inhabitant of the low-tech, junkyard city of Deponia who dreams of escaping to the advanced city of Elysium in the sky.  Early on an Elysian girl falls to Deponia and he sees this as his opportunity.  The game suffers from a slow start, but the story picks up later with some suspense & a satisfying ending.Progression is based on multi-screen environments and an inventory system, including combining/McGyvering items. It's a mix of common sense, critical thinking and trial and error. There is occasional frustration with sequence or dialogue, but you can click for audio commentary/hints on most things and press a key to see all the hotspots on screen.Beautiful, hand drawn art at 1080p with a minimalist interface that never feels cumbersome or gets in the way of the art, has Steam achievements and is fully voiced."
