,Not Recommended,214340,11478097,"Posted: 30 July, 2014",all,TARS,"Point and click adventure game in my opinion stand on three pillars as a genre, narrative, game aesthetics and the puzzle complexity. If any of these pillars suffers it could entirely break the game and make a bland if not a terrible experience. This is what happened in Deponia with its narrative that just utterly failed the game's mostly good puzzle and aesthetic design. I just found that I was never engaged with the protagonist or the overall narrative which lead me to simply turn off the game on multiple occasions because I just got bored of the entire affair. The worst part was that even when I finally did finish the game I was given that utterly vapid void of an ending that brings closure to nothing and essentially demands that I play the next Deponia game to get a better picture of the narrative, which just isn't going to happen when I couldn't give a rats♥♥♥♥♥about anything going on to begin with.  I definitely saw the potential in Deponia and I saw the reasons people like it, but I can't in good conscious bring myself to anything other than warn people not to play this game. This is something that I hate to do to game's since I'm a big adherent to the philosophy that a game can be good regardless of how long it is, but for 19.99 a six hour experience just isn't good value for money for the player and that isn't acceptable in my opinion especially when its a mediocre experience at best.If you want to read a more detailed review you can find it over here on my blog:http://mouseandcontroller.blogspot.com/2014/07/deponia.html."
76561198172049809,Not Recommended,214340,31138167,Posted: 14 April,all,Tin-Tin,"I’m certain I have finished this game but I was so bored and frustrated by the game I can’t really remember. I know and appreciate that many people enjoy this game, I really wanted to like it as it was my first attempt at seriously getting into point and click style games. The plot was lost on me at the very beginning, the dialogue was painful at best and all the characters annoyed me. I know there are a few other people who have a similar view as me, and I respect that other people love this game, I would recommend playing some via a friend’s accounts if they have it or watching videos and just seeing if you can enjoy the game before buying it. I KNOW IT IS ON SALE ALL THE TIME BUT PLEASE SEE HOLD OFF AND SEE IF YOU LIKE IT, for me it was like slow death by a cheese greater."
,Not Recommended,214340,33463595,Posted: 11 July,all,King Link,"So Deponia....Let's take two people. One is a guy who's trying to be a master pirate, and the other is a guy who wants to leave a dying world to go to a better world.  Which of these guys would be more likable?Well the first is Guybrush Threepwood of Monkey's Island,. and the second is Rufus of Deponia, and surprisingly Rufus is the unlikable character, but I'm getting ahead of myself.Rufus stars in Deponia, a technically proficient and beautiful game.  Deponia is about a world called Deponia, and Rufus, a man who wants to go to a magical place called Elysium, and no it's not the afterlife, and no it's not based off that film Elysium in 2013, though kind of the same plot.The difference between Elysium the movie and Deponia, is Rufus is unlikable and Matt Damon is one of the most charismatic actors out there.   Oh we're back to that again.  Well let's deal with it.You see, the problem with Deponia is that the comedy kind of centers around Rufus being well... I think any word I used about him would be censored.  At the beginning of the game, you see him make some poor judgements and you think he's a dope.  He's a bit of an jerk to the person he's living with but she's a bit of a jerk back so maybe it's just a situation of a roommate you don't like.But from there on... well Rufus just doesn't seem to get along with anyone.  It's not that he's a troublemaker, or at least it's not only that, he just seems to constantly be snarky with everyone to the point where he's a ... another name for a donkey.You see in games like this such as Monkey's Island, the main character works in a morally grey area, usually picking up everything they can and using it together to accomplish a goal.  Quite often the game shows that the player's actions can be seen as deviant or criminal, but they're necessary to proceed, they work towards a goal.On the other hand Rufus delights in all the misery he causes.  He laughs at times when he's doing awful actions, he directly hurts people, and snickers about it.  This isn't a ""I have to do this"" but rather a ""I enjoy doing this"" moment, and it's not exactly actions the player enjoys either so... Rufus comes off as unlikable.  Others have pointed out misogynistic tones in the character or game, and they exist, but the way Rufus treats everyone is just poor.Now that the main character is out of the way, what about the game itself.Well it's a point and click adventure, and I have to admit there's some clever moments in the game, but quite often you have a huge inventory of items, and no hint on what's the next thing to do.  There's points where you have a drill, a knife, a syringe and more, and often times you need to use a specific item to complete a task, but which item?  The game rarely gives you a hint.  Sadly there's a lot of trial and error required with this game and oftentimes that means use every item with every item and one will hopefully click.On the other hand if you miss something, well you're going to be out of luck.  There's very little hinting on the item.  For the first hour of the game, the game keeps the locations you need to visit to a minimum, but then once you meet the girl in the game (called Goal... yeah maybe there's something to the idea the game is misogynist) the game opens up and now there's tens of locations.The good news is there's a button that shows you all the interactable items on a screen, but again.  Use all your items on all the other items and hope you hit on the right combo quickly.    Or use a guide.And eventually you're probably going to have to use a guide or try entirely too many wrong combinations.The other issue I have with the game is the walk speed in the game is slow.   You can warp between rooms but just watching the main character walk between point a and point b is kind of a drag.  In other games the player might not move when an incorrect selection was made and just drop a clever quip or just ""I can't do that"" In this game, the character walks between the two points to even just look at an object, and this is a slow process.I mentioned before the game is beautiful and technically impressive, and it is, but the walk cycle could have been quicker.  A beautiful game will get duller the more times you have to look at the same location or object, and Deponia doesn't do enough to keep that beauty from being dulled by the main character, the slow walk speed, or just the obtuse puzzles.So I wouldn't recommend Deponia, I won't be picking up the sequels, but I can recommend some good point and click games to also consider.  Grim Fandango, Day of the Tentacle, Secret of Monkey's Island and machinarium are all rather good point and click games.  Deponia isn't a horrible game, but it's just that I have trouble recommending it because I just don't like it... but that's the thing, with Rufus as a main character, I'm not sure I'm supposed to like it."
,Not Recommended,214340,8586148,"Posted: 5 January, 2014",all,Lyrian,"I thought I would like this game because it had good reviews and was compared to the Monkey Island series. Instead we have a game that's misogynist, transphobic and obtuse with a main character so unlikeable that I just gave up on the game. I didn't care about the fact that it had hard puzzles or ones that made no sense. I was expecting that, but Rufus is such a♥♥♥♥♥♥that I'm sad I even spent two bucks on this game. You can tell that they put a lot of work into it. I love the art in the game, I like the way that it looks and it sounds (voice acting aside), but... I just can't get past how juvenile and bigoted the humour is. Maybe that's the point. Maybe it's trying to be ironic in the way of South Park by being absolutely horrible for comedic effect and to draw attention to how stupid these tropes/stereotypes/etc sound.But the problem with Deponia trying to do that? It's not funny. The jokes fall flat, the dialogue gets painful to listen to and I have never wished so much that there was a big cliff that I could just throw Rufus off over and over again."
,Not Recommended,214340,20096751,"Posted: 29 December, 2015",all,laker,"Disclaimer: This is just for people who don't play Adventure games and are trying to get into them.I don't think this one will help you. It didn't help me.I don't usually play adventure games but when I do ... I don't.I was really looking forward to Deponia. Because of the graphic style and because of the humor. And it was fun at first.BUT: Then came the Adventuring part. Taking everything you see, trying to combine it and somehow figure out how to use something on something else. At first I've tried to figure everything by myself. Later I've started to look at the guide, here and there. And after a while I've found myself looking at it more or less constantly. Those things just don't make any sense to me. I don't know why would I knock out a parrot with laughing gas and I don't know what I would do with him afterwards.I don't doubt that Deponia is a great game. For people who like adventure games. But if you don't like adventure games, Deponia isn't for you despite how gorgeous it looks, how funny it can be, and how great the voice acting is.I'm really sad that I couldn't enjoy it. But I won't play game by reading a guide."
76561198024980613,Not Recommended,214340,11054678,"Posted: 3 July, 2014",all,Inky_Petrel,"While the art is cool, and the world concept is a fun one, the gross sexism in this game made it completely horrible to play.  Female characters are only there as a joke or a quest, and the writing continually enforces this attitude.   Hell, the main female character is CALLED Goal.  *eyeroll*  And the driving force for Rufus is to win her.As well as this, Rufus constantly tells us that cleaning is a woman's role (specifically his ex Toni) and that ""girly things"" are beneath  him.  There's also a trans woman played as a joke (""ha ha look at the big man in a dress""  Yeah, no, not actually funny.)Clearly this is all meant to be funny, and to endear Rufus to us as a ""charming rogue"".  A clue, it doesn't, he isn't.  He's a creeper, and the way he acts towards the unconcious/brain damaged Goal is creepy, gross, bordering on rapey.  His friend Wendel is also nasty.    The whole game has a greasy vibe.It's a real shame, because technically it's not a bad game.  The movement is a bit slow and clunky, and it can be frustrating to get from one point to another,  but otherwise it does okay.  I would have been interested to play similar games if the whole thing didn't leave me feeling like I needed a shower.  As it is, don't bother.  Spend your money on a game that gives its female characters some agency, and its male characters some redeeming character traits.So very glad I got this on sale, not worth it."
