,Recommended,214340,35003023,Posted: 16 September,all,Dr.Larry,"Oh man, flicking through my library and seeing this game and the sequels I can't help but have fond memories of my playthrough.It probably took me about 6 or so hours to beat but it was great. It's games like Deponia that really remind you why adventure games were such a huge genre back in the day while also making you feel a bit sad when you realise the genre is pretty much seen as a niche now. Understandable given games have evolved to be more action orientated and less focused on delivering a story or strong narrative but that's not to say there still isn't a place for adventure games to shine.Deponia is definitely one of those games that shines and brings the genre to the forefront. It's got a great cast, some really good voice acting and great writing. The puzzles, however... They're not that great. They do fit the quirky theme and setting but they're very random, very frustrating and you will most likely find yourself looking at a guide every now and then if not you're left with mixing all sorts of random items together in random areas and picking up things you didn't think you could pick up to combine with some of the weirdest things ever.To put into scope how weird and how out there some of these puzzles are, there's one in particular where you have to get in a crane and operate it. When you fix it and put everything in it you're missing one last step but the game never hints at what it is, Rufus simply voices that something isn't right. What it turns out to be is the skeleton sitting in the seat before had it's leg up behind the seat so, what you have to do is grab the skeleton's leg, jam it behind the seat(After removing the skeleton) and then operate the crane. That's how crazy and how confusing some of the puzzles can be in this game.Other than that it's one of the best adventure games to date in my opinion. I loved the characters, the story was good -- it was no Tolken epic now -- and interesting enough and the world, it's setting and the atmosphere was fantastic. It did a good job of delivering a somewhat slapstick, chilled experience which I loved about it.Great game, well worth picking up for the price it is now although the complete edition(Includes the first three games) is on sale regularly enough for about €15 so if you think you might be interested just pick that version up as it includes everything bar the very last game.Absolutely recommend this if you're at all looking for anything that resembles an adventure game. Worth the €9.99 for the first game alone."
