,Not Recommended,214340,7972577,"Posted: 8 December, 2013",all,TheKarpuk,"I'll fully admit I bought this for the art style. In that regard, Deponia is exactly what it advertises. The chunky, eccentric designs of characters and backgrounds really brings this game to life.And that's where the praise ends.The big issue here is the writing, and it commits what is, to me, the greatest sin. It's trying to be funny. The jokes come at you on a regular basis. But I did not laugh once in my entire playthrough. Perhaps it's because of the mean nature of much of the humor, or it's a style that just doesn't carry over in translation, but most of the time the characters just seemed unlikable and mean-spirited.My thought is that if you don't get laughs, stop it. Just stop it. Tell a story, be earnest in your delivery, drop all the affected attempts at hilarity. Maybe then they could have spent more time on the puzzles, which range from arbitrary to insulting.There's a puzzle where you literally have to make an association between the house a person lives in and what their hat is, because three people all have headgear that looks like their occupation. It's that sort of backwards engineered idiot puzzle that makes people give up on adventure games. It has to be logical, sensible but not obvious, or the player will just give up.This is the sort of series I'd rather view through one of those ""Let's Play"" Youtube series, but preferrably with the sound off."
76561198045148402,Not Recommended,214340,32120145,Posted: 1 June,all,JZStudios,"This game just has too many issues and things to dislike.On the plus side, the music, visuals, and voice acting are all quite good. The spacebar also highlights selectable items in the world, which makes things a bit easier.I had/noticed some technical issues where the mouse would register the wrong click or not register at all. The subtitles are full of typos, despite being translated by a London based group and being voice acted. Those are small issues and easy to overlook, but the story and characters are not.The story is barebones as can possibly be, and is still not explained much. You get the what, but not the who or why. It makes it just feel like a super generic bad guy and you really just don't care. It's pretty evident that they expected to make a series, further reinforced by the cheesy question mark after the end. I'd like to give a synopsis, but it would take about 2 sentences and cover the entire story. [spoileri]You play Rufus, an unlikeable character who just wants to get off his trash heap planet to a floating space station named Elysium. During his failed attempt he knocks a girl off a vessel... thing, who turns out to be the fiance of the main bad guy who wants to blow up the planet.[/spoileri] There's literally no explanation at all, and the villian is just about the same level as Dr. Robotnik, not even close to Bowser.There's also a third group of... androids?... Maybe? They're called metal beards at one point and seem to be magnetic, but this is just something else with zero explanation.None of the characters are flushed out enough to care about any of them, much less the one character you're stuck with the whole game.  Rufus is terrible. He makes a few quips that can be humurous, but for the most part just cries and whines about having to do literally anything. The entire game, along with other characters constantly shove it in your face about how much you don't care about his whiny self centered personality, but only seems to idolize it and makes no attempts to change it. [spoileri]He has no redeeming qualities throughout the game, his only motivation is leaving the planet and banging the unconcious engaged girl. At the end he takes the place of her fiance as she has lost her memory but instead decides to tell her the truth. I suppose this could be his redeeming quality moment, but when it's literally an entire planet vs. your chub I just don't find it that redeeming.[/spoileri] He's not dislikeable in a good way like a well made villian, he's just flat out that annoying person that no one likes, and lucky you get to spend about 8 hours with him.All the other characters may as well be nonexistant, but not mentioning the apparently hot piece of Ginger Elysian Goal would be a mistake, as she's the driving ""plot"" device. She's unconcious for 96% of the game, in which time Rufus constantly calls her ""babe"" and his girlfriend, despite never actually talking to her aside from when she told you to call her fiance. When she finally actually wakes up by the end, she initially tells Rufus to not call her babe, then about 30 seconds later she apparently loves him.. I guess... for some reason... I'm actually not really sure. The whole thing is just kind of creepy and weird.The last complaint is the super obtuse puzzles. Maybe it's just because I don't play much adventure/point'n'click games, but I just don't understand the type of mental connections you'd have to have for these puzzles to make sense. One involves a parrot and a couple kittens, which goes through a rather ridiculous process, and one involves a skeletons leg to meditate. Or rather, not involve it? Just for spoilers sake, here's the explanation of these puzzles:Parrot:[spoileri] In order to get to a radio, you need to stop the post office from functioning. The radio also requires headphones found on an operator near some carrier pigeons. So what you need to do is make a drugged blowdart to take out your ex girlfriend and steal some vouchers. Then you get a magnetic field tablet thing, switch some lights around which switch the pigeons to the wrong hole. You then need to drug one cat, give ""espresso"" to another, and give the post man robot a stolen voucher, which then sends a package to nowhere. The postage is incorrect and the postbot has to rebox the package with bubble wrap, which you then need to walk over to distract postbot. You then grab some spare kittens and a cypher to decode the lock to the radio room where you get a nodding bird. You place one kitten on a button and the nodding bird on the other.You still with me so far? Good, because that's the part that made sense. The parrot follows.From here you then need to go to a completely different area. This alone I just don't find good. The whole point is there's 3 lines of communication you need to block, the kitten and bird taking care of two, You once again to reiterate go to a completely different area and I don't understand how this logic is supposed to work. Just even guessing that you need the parrot is a hell of a stretch.You fill a balloon with laughing gas and knock out the parrot, shove it in your coat and then inexplicably give it to your ex. You have to leave and come backto find out she's apparently been telling it of all your crimes (again to reinforce that you're a ♥♥♥♥♥♥ character.) Steal the parrot and put it on the phone with the police guy.Huzzah! Headphones are now yours to steal. By comparison, you also needed a microphone, which was down the hall and you just pick it up. [/spoileri]It's a bit ridiculous, but the skeleton leg is worse.[spoileri] At one point you need to operate a crane, but apparently you're too nervous... for some reason, which results in dropping chubbait Goal about 25 feet directly onto her spine. You talk to a man who teaches you how to meditate, followed by taking a swig of alcohol. You then need to do the meditation thing again (because now you know you need his alcohol) and siphon some of his drink into your own empty bottle. This part's fine, but what follows angered me probably a lot too much. After following the same procedure and having it not work and dropping Goal from 25 feet onto her spine the second time something seems amiss. So here's the ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t. Apparently the skeleton leg you picked up earlier that has had zero use whatsoever is meant to go behind the seat for absolutely no reason whatsoever. Literally zero.The ""meditation tutorial was literally click on the horizon, watch some flashy colors, take a swig. So where the ♥♥♥♥ does the leg come into play? It makes exactly zero sense whatsoever. It's complete and utter ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t and I'm glad I had a guide, because if I spent 15-20 minutes to either find out on my own through randomly clicking on♥♥♥♥♥♥or giving up and checking a guide anyways, I would've been absolutely♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ At least the stupid runaround with the parrot had a reason. It was dumb, but it was a reason. Having a puzzle requirement with two objects that have ZERO involvement with the puzzle at hand is stupendously asanineI... I just can't even begin to understand the line of thinking that comes from. Absolutely terrible.I'm not sure where to drop this in, but once you toss the leg behind you to meditate and get drunk, you pick up Goal and drop her about 30 feet onto the back of a minecart for a grand total of every broken bone in her body before you ride off into the sunset for the games final ♥♥♥♥♥♥ ending act.[/spoileri]"
,Not Recommended,214340,34156113,Posted: 10 August,all,[TSC] TheHolyDarkness,"When you require a walkthrough within the first few minutes of the game because the game designer hides a key object behind your character, you know something is going to be wrong.This isn't a game with multiple solutions to the puzzles. The cryptic game design wants to you figure things out in a very specifically scripted way with zero clue as to what the hell the game designer was thinking. There's no internal puzzle logic within the context of the design. No clues, just snarky commentary as you try to do something that might make sense, only be to told you're wrong (and sometimes, only barely, like needing to use a blowdart on a window, rather than the target, in order to use the necessary blowdart on the target).Hours of aimlessly frustrated wandering around, and soon you'll be wondering why you're still playing.When ""puzzles"" (more like cryptically hidden scripted events) absolutely REQUIRE a walkthrough to complete, and, upon looking up the solutions, the player can't help but think ""AW COME ON!"" or ""WHAT THE HELL I TRIED THAT ALREADY DIDN'T I?!"" you know you have a problem with your game design.Thus, I give up by the time I reached the junk yard area, where apparently I'm missing an item (even after interacting with every known object in the vicinity and consulting a walkthrough). You can try to get further than I, but you won't have fun doing so.What you'll have is boredom or a headache. That's all this game has to give. Hard to enjoy it's laughs with such stonewalled pacing.I'm bored.  z_zConclusion:Pass on this one. Not even at 90% off is this game worth it.Truly a pity, as the art design, voice acting, and writing was promising so much.Whoever made this should stick to web comics."
,Not Recommended,214340,29756780,Posted: 6 February,all,Smegmatron,"I tend to like these types of games, and usually can get an easy recommendation from me.  Deponia has some decent humor to it, but will constantly do little things to annoy the♥♥♥♥♥♥out of you.  Many of the puzzles just simply don't make sense.  It may seem completely obvious that doing something you have in mind should work, but the writers would rather you do it their way, which makes less sense.  This is a minor flaw, though.  The bigger flaw is that the game is downright buggy.  If you skim through the discussion forums you'll see a lot of problems the game has, and the devs only solution is to download a new save file.  Even with known issues, the game doesn't seem to get patched, and you're simply stuck with downloading a different save file, which could throw your own game out of sequence.  I usually want to complete games like this, but this has made me lose my motivation to finish it, even as I have the sequels in my library waiting to be played, but will now likely never be installed."
