,Recommended,214340,17744634,"Posted: 27 August, 2015",all,Esyntha,"I really like these style of games. They are point and click adventures with alot of heart and polish reminiscent of monkey island. I definitely reccomend this game but with one huge caveat.Minor spoiler?;;;;;;The protagonist is an unlikable♥♥♥♥♥♥. He is the type of person whom you do not readily want to know and I almost want to see him fail. I had to quit the second game with he pretty much made a decision for me instead of going with the answer I chose (it was supposed to be funny  when he had to get a high quality item but instead he got the low quality one that came with a lolipop...) which infuriated me, why give a choice if its meaningless?"
76561197979170276,Recommended,214340,28970195,Posted: 3 January,all,AFWump,"Bottom line up-front:Should you buy this game: If you enjoy point-and-click adventures, YesPro's:+ Great art syle+ Memorable, but brief characters+ Funny story with a likable protagonist.+ Good music with original songsCon's+ Obstuse puzzle solutions+ Short story legnth+ Not enough interation with many unique charactersReviewDeponia (first in a series of four games) is at its heart, a throw-back to the early point and click adventure games first popularized by Sierra-Online in the 80's and early 90s'.It follows the misadventures of Rufus, a self-centered, self-aggrandizing, self-destructive, yet lovable transient bum, who is trying desperately to escape the perpetual junk filled planet of Deponia for the floating paradise in the sky known as Elysium. As the opening exposition tells us on the outset of the game, he will concoct any manner of schemes or contraptions in order to achieve his goal, and Lord help anyone, or anything that stands in his way.  I just wish I had a chance to interact with them more and see them fleshed out more fully.And speaking of goals, Rufus quickly crosses paths with Goal, a beautiful Elysium woman who is, shall we say...not right in the head.  Which as Rufus will attest, that her condition had absolutely nothing to do with knocking her off the unprotected deck of a passing cruiser deck, plummeting to the ground and damaging her brain's hardware, rendering her unconscious. Goal represents the more cultured and educated foil to Rufus's blunt and unrefined nature, but the revelation later that her memories and personality can be changed via data cartriges placed in her brain implant, seemed a little off-putting.  I realize that it was written that way for comedic effect, but it still created a few cringeworthy moments.What follows is Rufus' travels to return Goal to Elysium and ""unselfishly"" earning him a complimentary admission ticket to the golden city (my words).Deponia has a lot to like. The first thing that is apparent about Deponia, is the cartoonish art-style.  Deponia is a literal world of junk, and everything in their society is constructed out what looks like the largest garbage dump known to man. Houses, buildings, everyday objects look like they were cobbled together out of repurposed items that were thrown away.The cartoon style also gives life to all of the characters.  Even the bit-part characters are uniquely designed and animated. Each one has their own personality, and backstory, which isn't told through a lot of needless and awkward exposition.  This also highlights the smart and clever writing. Through a few well-placed sentences, you can already grasp who the individual characters are.  I truly got the sense that this game could have been its own animated comedy series on television, and it would have held up.While the cartoon comedy provides a lot of this games positives, there are a few downsides to this game.  Let's start with the puzzles.  The cartoonish nature of the game requires you to think as if you were in a cartoon environment. Which means that puzzles are deceptively easy, in that you have to think in very sideways terms, where most people will take a more literal approach.  For example, you are given instructions on how to assume a certain sitting pose to go into a meditative trance.  One of those instructions is to sit and place your left leg behind your head. When you get the place where you have to meditate, there is no place, or option to manipulate the character into the proper position. That is, until you take the leg from a skeleton, and place it behind you.  Many of the solutions will leave you groaning in both laughter, and frustration.Next are the mini-games.  There are a few of these sprinkled about in the game, but they have little to no explanation as to how they work, or how to achieve a solvable state. This will leave you scratching your head for hours, while you struggle to derive some kind of meaning of the game from the few, or lack or clues as to how they work.  Fortunately, the developers left an option to skip these mini-games, if you wish.Despite these flaws, I still think Deponia is worth its price-point.  It is funny, well-written, leaves room open for its sequels.  If you like these kinds of games, definitely give it a try. However, buy the bundle pack and stretch your money a little further."
