76561198071106517,Not Recommended,214340,19444986,"Posted: 2 December, 2015",all,tattoogunman,"I was around when games like Space Quest, Kings Quest, Police Quest, Leisure Suit Larry, etc. were the popular games that basically popularized the ""point and click"" genre.  As such, I still enjoy these types of games and it's nice to see someone making them again.  That said.......I like the art style in the game, I like the music, sound effects, and all of that.  I can deal with a slow moving character, as hair pulling as it may be sometimes.  My only real complaint with this game is, unfortunately, what it's about and that is solving puzzles.I like solving puzzles and I like a challenging puzzle as much as the next person.  Where these games generally excelled in the past is that while challenging, you were still provided sufficient clues to figure out how to get through the games.  This was back in the days before the internet, walk through guides, Youtube videos, and all of that stuff.  Where this game has infuriated me is the puzzles - I do not think that I should have to consult walk through guides in order to complete a game and that is what I find myself doing time and time again.  Judging from other reviews, so have other people.  Again, there was a time where you could find clues in the environment or failing that, after a few failed attempts, your character might offer something helpful - not here.You will need to backtrack to areas that you thought you were done with and generally don't get any prompting to go back to (or even know you can get back to).  You will sometimes need to go back to the same room multiple times in order to find items that should have all been available the first time you were there (unlockables or things of that nature notwithstanding).  You will be required to interact with certain things in the environment, that you thought you were done with, multiple times in order to proceed (I'm not giving examples so as not to ruin for those who haven't played it yet).  There are times where you may have to manipulate the same nonplayable character multiple times to achieve the desired result (with no prompting or hinting that this is necessary to ultimately elicit the required response/result).  The mini games present inside the main game give you no prompting, clues, or hints as to what you are supposed to do to get them to work or how to solve them in most cases.  There are times where you click on everything in the environment and try using everything in your inventory, just to find out none of it works because you didn't realize you have to backtrack to the beginning of the game or some other area you thought you were done with to proceed.  Of course there are other times where what you are supposed to do is blatantly obvious  - I just wish they could have found a middle ground someplace with this.So for those reasons, I am not recommending this game.  If you don't mind having to cheat to get through the game by consulting walk through guides, then give it a shot if it's on sale or offered as a bundle."
