,Recommended,214340,8237974,"Posted: 23 December, 2013",all,OmegaJeff,"While I did enjoy this game for its lovely art style and its classic 90s era take on the adventure genre, I can only recommend this first entry in the series with some reservations.  The dystopian setting of the titular Deponia is a literal trash heap orbited by the idyllic Elysium (not to be confused with the blockbuster movie of the same name, with the same plot).  The cartooniness dulls the edge of the grim setting, but there's still some hearty meat to it.  This first entry explores much of what there is worth exploring, and the ending feels solid enough that you can easily leave it there without further sequels.However, throughout the game the central character Rufus becomes more and more insufferable.  He's endearing at first, but near the end of the game it starts to become exhausting.  For this first entry, it's not quite a deal breaker.  But by the start of the sequel, he gets to the point of being completely intolerable.  While it's obvious they're trying to channel Guybrush Threepwood, it crosses some hard to define line at some point and he becomes so grating you just can't help but turn it off."
