,Recommended,214340,16196118,"Posted: 4 June, 2015",all,Tizzie,"Personally, I have never been a fan of point and click games, however, Deponia has entirely changed that.I originally batted about the idea of purchasing Deponia because the art style really appealed to me, but I was put off by the play style and the price. However, when it came on sale for £0.79 I snapped it up without a second thought, as, even if I were only to use it for artistic reference, I knew I wouldn’t regret spending that on it. It is probably the best thing I’ve ever bought for under a pound. Immediately, I was hooked. It is fun and immersive, and, though it appears to have some childish tones, the dialogue and extremely well-developed characters provide many humorous moments and you start to see that it is rather adult in its comedic value.Then there’s the difficulty. I never imagined that a point and click adventure would prove so taxing! The hidden objects, the combinations required, the little puzzles and the specific orders required for the completion of tasks often left me scratching my head and, I will admit, if I hadn’t had the opportunity to glance at a walk through on the odd occasion, I doubt I would be anywhere near completing it right now (though I avoided using the guide as much as possible, of course). I’ve still not unlocked all of the achievements!I am not entirely sure whether it has a lot of replay value, but I know I will be coming back to it simply because I will miss the atmosphere and the quirky characters! And I will admit, though Rufus is an egocentric jerk and possibly one of the worst boyfriends in gaming history, he is very loveable and under it all, a real sweetheart.The only thing I can complain about with Deponia is the fact that it is too short, and the prices on the series are a bit high for my liking, but the moment the sequels come on sale I will be snapping them up!So yes, I whole-heartedly recommend this game. It is beautiful, the sound track is super funky, the characters are funny and unique and it does supply a good challenge to keep your mind occupied.Plus, my toothbrush ran away and hid in a dark corner, mocking me from the shadows, and I made coffee out of battery acid and gave it to a cat who licked stamps… What’s not to love?10/10"
