76561198064599475,Not Recommended,214340,15830362,"Posted: 14 May, 2015",all,Rudedog,"This game taught me something.  Namely, you cannot have an utterly vile protagonist in an adventure game because that undermines my willingness to advance the plot.  Some of the things Rufus does (that you are absolutely required to do to advance the plot) are monstrous.  All the other characters in the game hate Rufus and by the end of the game I did too.  I guess I'm just not malevolent enough to laugh at Rufus's antics.[Minor Spoiler Alert]For Example, during the third act of the game, you find out that his love interest, the girl he's been dragging around like luggage the entire game has a hard drive in her head that contains her memories and personality.  You are told the reason she is catatonic and speaks in gibberish is because it's damaged but later learn it only has dust on it's contact points.  You are warned sternly that even minor scratches could leave her a vegi.  So what do you do? ""Clean"" it with a gross pool cleaner brush then use a steel brush to buff it before carving R Heart G in the contact point like it's a tree.  And that's after explicitly finding gentler methods and rejecting them as ""girly"".  I've never been so revolted.So yeah, the writting spoiled the game for me.  I simply cannot abide being forced to do lothesome things to accomplish some random, short term goal.  It's sad too because the art was beautiful, the animation decent for the genre, the supporting characters were somewhat interesting, and the puzzles were... well they were all over the map for quality and tilted toward ""mash together evertything you've ever laid hands on"" but they were mostly fun.  Still this game had the humor of little boys who get off on kicking pets and spiking the punch bowl at a party with laxatives.  If that discribes you, dive in.  Otherwise run far away."
