76561198000281653,Recommended,214340,11094971,"Posted: 5 July, 2014",all,Linni Visay,"Deponia is a beautifully produced point-and-click comedy adventure game, that mangages to tell a very old story (boy saves girl from evil pursuers) in a fun and interesting way. In particular, I felt the standout feature was the antihero protagonist, an uncommon and hard-to-pull off choice.When I first loaded up Deponia, the thing that first stuck me was the art style, which really reminded me of Lucasarts ""The Curse of Monkey Island"", which was the first adventure game I ever played. I think the cartoony style really lends itself to adventure games of this sort.At first, the protagonist Rufus reminded me a lot of Monkey Island's Guybrush Threepwood (even the voice acting is similar), but as you play through the game you realise Rufus isn't a bumbling idiot with a heart of gold, but rather a selfish egotist filled with the desire to leave the trash planet of Deponia at any cost.  The writers did a really good job of creating a repellent character that we nevertheless empathise with and want to help succeed, which is hard to do. Other characters are fun, although I would have liked the damsel in distress, Goal, to find her voice a bit sooner. She really only comes to her senses in the last sequence of the game, after being badly injured in the first sequence.On a general level, the story is interesting because it very clearly only tells the first arc of a standard story. Because Deponia now has two sequels, this isn't the problem for me that it would have been for those who played it on release. I don't own the sequels, but I can grab them whenever I want to continue the story. For anyone who played it on release, it may have been a bit of a hanging ending. For that reason, even though I didn't, I'd recommend buying all three games at once.The puzzles would be considered easy by someone who started on the early adventure games in the pre-internet era, but I consider that a wholly good thing - the game loses all flow if you can't solve a puzzle. I only got stuck twice - once was from not thinking/acting like Rufus would and missing an interaction, and once because an item was slightly unclear about exactly what it was. The game also has ""highlight interactables"" and ""skip minigame"" functions to make it a bit easier if you want.As with most point-and-click games, replayability is severely diminished after you've won the game once, as there is only one way to play the game. The developers do kind of cheekily allude to this with the inclusion of droggeljug mode.All in all, Deponia is a good adventure game for the library."
,Recommended,214340,11096879,"Posted: 5 July, 2014",all,Vero,"DO NOT PLAY THIS GAME IN ENGLISH. Play it in German with the subtitles of your choice. The English dub is terrible. If you play it in German, the characters are interesting, the plot is pretty fun, and the ending is a little disappointing because it's trying to set you up for the next game. Even with the ending and terrible English dub, it's still a fun game. It gets Bonus Points for being a good way to brush up on your German.Droggeljug."
