,Recommended,214340,11945349,"Posted: 1 September, 2014",all,Bug,"This game is different from the usual point and click games. It reminded me a lot of Pajama Sam, a favorite classic PC game of mine. It's more adult based, of course, in comparison to Pajama Sam. Between the snarky comments, adult-related hints and crude comedy, there's the point and click along with the story line. The main character, Rufus, who you play, is the core of most of the comments, and much of the comedy. There's a few parts I don't agree with, like unnessary speech options that don't do anything or cause any different outcome. (Like rude, mean comments won't let you progress. It's a trial and error sort of thing, until you find the right speech option which sometimes can be conflicting with another positive comment.) It has a nice story, but many of the puzzles aren't so obvious like 'go here, do this, for this thing that you need for this 'quest' '. The game gives you a singular hint, and leaves you to it. Much of the gameplay can end up being running around in circles, trying to figure out what you're meant to be doing. Despite this, I still recommend the game for the story and comedy. I would rate the difficulty at 'moderate'. If you're good at puzzle, and point and click games, you'll probably love this game."
76561198039108757,Recommended,214340,11940836,"Posted: 31 August, 2014",all,Captin,"The first of the series. The beginning of the chaos and your journey into a Machinarium-like world with all the maddening puzzles included. Be aware that this is no mere logic-based puzzle game as nothing you do will make any since unless you're MacGyver.It's an unusual love story set in a world divided by classes, or those who were left behind. The style is very similar to a painting or comic book, with semi-fluid animations and an odd soundtrack to bring it to life. This game of the series had some rough voice acting however, which improved over the next two games naturally.You may get frustrated with some of the puzzles not making sense, it's on purpose, and I think this may have had a more negative impact on players than expected. The story and goofiness of it all helps recover the games balance though."
