,Not Recommended,214340,22162741,"Posted: 31 March, 2016",all,The Jumping Ghost,"$20 for this ?  Fortunately I got the game for only $2 on sale, but I can't help imagining how disappointed I would have been if I had paid full price for it.  10 hours is no small amount of game time but the plot barely advances at all over the course of the game.  Half of my time playing was spent making a cup of espresso, and the rest of the game just rushes by without anything actually happening.  The game ended right when I thought it was getting started.  None of the questions that were introduced in the exposition of the game were resolved at the end, and instead it only made the story even more ambiguous without any closure.  This game is completely useless without owning the sequels, which only seems like a way of cheaply breaking up the story for more money, when this one is being sold at twice the price that it should be.This game showed a lot of promise at the start.  It's set in a unique and interesting world that I had no problem getting into (in no small part due to the phenomenal art direction), the protagonist is a relatably uncharismatic outcast who became increasingly likable as his surroundings (namely his disdainful and unsympathetic neighbors) became more developed, the hero's actions and motives are clear and understandable despite his overt rudeness and dim-witted sense of grandiosity, it has an engaging sense of humor, and the good soundtrack and voice acting only added to the charm of the game.  With so much done right, it's incredible that anything could go wrong.Unfortunately the plot just becomes a mess once the final area is reached and the last chunk of story is delivered all at once just before it's abruptly ended.  The last area consists of a frustrating back and forth that ultimately brings the protagonist right back to the start just when it felt like the game was finally getting somewhere, that is Elysium, the place that the player and the character have both been trying to reach the whole time.  It gets so close to reaching this goal that it felt like the real plot was artificially snatched away at the last second simply so that a sequel could be made.My suggestion is that you should play this game if it looks appealing, but be prepared to get forced into a whole series and definitely do not buy it at full price.  I personally enjoyed Deponia and will probably be buying the game's sequels myself if they go on sale sometime, but I can't recommend playing it at the current price of $20."
